Subject: in_dxf: don't strlen() the whole remaining buffer per character

dxf_read_string's per-character loop probes each byte for a "\M+n" MIF
escape with memBEGINc, whose implementation calls strlen(s1). Here s
points into the raw file buffer, so every character of every string
value scanned the entire remaining file: DXF import cost O(file_size^2).
A 19 MB DXF (a real pavement-details plan exported by ezdxf) needed
minutes of pure strlen before this and converts in seconds after.

Compare the three escape bytes directly with an explicit bounds check
against dat->size — faster and safer than relying on a terminating NUL
in a memory-mapped buffer.

Found by IngeCAD's round-trip fidelity harness over a corpus of 1385
real-world DWGs (same hunt as #1311-#1315).

Co-authored-by: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>

--- a/src/in_dxf.c
+++ b/src/in_dxf.c
@@ -658,7 +658,11 @@ dxf_read_string (Bit_Chain *dat, char **string)
            dat->byte++)
         {
           char *s = (char *)&dat->chain[dat->byte];
-          if (memBEGINc (s, "\\M+") && s[3] >= '1' && s[3] <= '5')
+          // Compare the 3 bytes directly: memBEGINc would strlen() the whole
+          // remaining multi-MB buffer for EVERY character of EVERY string,
+          // making DXF import quadratic in file size (a 19 MB DXF "hangs").
+          if (dat->byte + 3 < dat->size && s[0] == '\\' && s[1] == 'M'
+              && s[2] == '+' && s[3] >= '1' && s[3] <= '5')
             {
               const Dwg_Codepage mif_tbl[]
                   = { CP_UNDEFINED, CP_ANSI_932,  CP_ANSI_950,
